 </office:automatic-styles>
 <office:master-styles>
  <style:master-page style:name="Standard" style:page-layout-name="pm1"/>
 </office:master-styles>
 <office:body>
  <office:text text:use-soft-page-breaks="true">
   <text:sequence-decls>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Illustration"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Table"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Text"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Drawing"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Figure"/>
   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_2" text:outline-level="2">Report: Demonstration of Object-Oriented Programming in the SGC System</text:h>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">Introduction</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">The SGC system, written in Java, is designed to manage and analyze student assessment data across various modules and provide detailed reports. The system exemplifies core Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) principles, including encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, and abstraction. This report explains how these OOP concepts have been applied throughout the system.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">1. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Encapsulation</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Encapsulation refers to bundling data and methods that operate on that data within classes and restricting direct access to some of the object’s components.</text:p>
   <text:list xml:id="list2323025376" text:style-name="L1">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P2"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Private Fields and Public Getters/Setters</text:span>:<text:line-break/>For example, the <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> class has private fields like <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">assessmentID</text:span>, <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">type</text:span>, and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">awardedMarks</text:span>. Access to these fields is provided through public getter methods (<text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getAssessmentID()</text:span>, <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getType()</text:span>, etc.). This hides internal representation and protects data integrity. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P1"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Controlled Access</text:span>:<text:line-break/>The use of private fields ensures that assessment details cannot be arbitrarily changed from outside the class, promoting data integrity. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">2. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Inheritance</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Inheritance allows a class to inherit properties and behaviors from a parent class, promoting code reuse.</text:p>
   <text:list xml:id="list1924072867" text:style-name="L2">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P4"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"> Base Class and Subclasses</text:span>:<text:line-break/>The abstract class <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> serves as a base for two concrete subclasses: <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Exam</text:span> and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Coursework</text:span>. Both inherit common properties such as <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">assessmentID</text:span>, <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">moduleID</text:span>, and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">awardedMarks</text:span>, reducing code duplication. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P3"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Specialized Behavior in Subclasses</text:span>:<text:line-break/><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Exam</text:span> introduces additional properties like <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">maxMarks</text:span> and overrides methods to compute grades based on maximum marks, while <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Coursework</text:span> handles marks differently. This shows inheritance coupled with specialization. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">3. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Polymorphism</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Polymorphism allows the same interface or method to behave differently based on the object it is acting on.</text:p>
   <text:list xml:id="list2305283618" text:style-name="L3">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P6"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Abstract Methods and Method Overriding</text:span>:<text:line-break/>The abstract methods <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getGrade()</text:span> and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getContribution()</text:span> in <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> are implemented differently in <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Exam</text:span> and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Coursework</text:span>. When these methods are called on an <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> reference, the appropriate subclass implementation executes. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P5"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Usage in Computations</text:span>:<text:line-break/><text:soft-page-break/>For example, when calculating module scores in <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Module.getModuleScore()</text:span>, the code iterates over a list of <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> objects and calls <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getContribution()</text:span> polymorphically. This allows seamless handling of both exams and coursework assessments without explicit type checks. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">4. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Abstraction</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Abstraction involves exposing only necessary components to the outside while hiding complex implementation details.</text:p>
   <text:list xml:id="list2212167013" text:style-name="L4">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Abstract </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"> Class</text:span>:<text:line-break/>The <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> class hides the complexity of how grades and contributions are computed. Clients interact with assessments through the public interface, without needing to know whether it is an exam or coursework. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P7"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Student and Module Classes</text:span>:<text:line-break/>These classes abstract the underlying data details. For instance, the <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Student</text:span> class provides a simple method <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">getDegreeScore()</text:span> to calculate the overall degree score, hiding the details of module score calculations, level filtering, and lowest module removal. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">5. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Other Notable OOP Concepts</text:span></text:h>
   <text:list xml:id="list296961932" text:style-name="L5">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Composition and Aggregation</text:span>: </text:p>
     <text:list>
      <text:list-item>
       <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Student</text:span> contains a list of <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Module</text:span> objects, and <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Module</text:span> contains a list of <text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> objects. This models real-world relationships (a student enrolls in modules, modules have assessments) clearly and naturally. </text:p>
      </text:list-item>
     </text:list>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Separation of Concerns</text:span>:<text:line-break/>Each class has a focused responsibility: </text:p>
     <text:list>
      <text:list-item>
       <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Assessment</text:span> models individual assessments. </text:p>
      </text:list-item>
      <text:list-item>
       <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Module</text:span> handles groups of assessments and their scoring. </text:p>
      </text:list-item>
      <text:list-item>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text">Student</text:span> handles overall student information and degree calculation.<text:line-break/>This separation makes the code easier to maintain and extend. </text:p>
      </text:list-item>
     </text:list>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">6. <text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis">Summary</text:span></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">Your implementation effectively leverages OOP principles to create a modular, extensible, and maintainable system. Key aspects demonstrated include:</text:p>
   <text:list xml:id="list1327386390" text:style-name="L6">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P12">Encapsulation of data with controlled access. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P12">Inheritance to promote reuse and specialization. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P12">Polymorphism enabling flexible behavior depending on assessment type. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P12">Abstraction to provide clean interfaces hiding internal complexity. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P11">Composition modeling relationships among students, modules, and assessments. </text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body">These principles collectively help manage the complexity of the system while keeping code clean and reusable.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
</office:document>